track_notes: 0.5 mile off-trail hike with 430 EG (take a bit off of thos figures to just to get to the AZ).  Park at Bearpen Gap pull-off on the BRP.  At the northern end of the parking lot is an access trail for the Mountains to Sea Trail.  Take a few steps into the woods, turn left and head up the ridgeline, staying in the woods the whole way.  If you venture out into the the thorny open areas, you will quickly regret it.  To get to the summit proper, you will have to traverse about 100 yards of open space and thorns (which may only be practical in the winter).  There are some extremely nice views from the summit so there is some reward for actually getting there.  But, you will enter the Activation Zone before you reach the open area before the summit and there is no reason to deal with the thorns if you dont want to.

I noticed an old trailbed shortly before reaching the summit on the western approach and decided to explore this route on the way down.  There is parking for one or two cars on the shoulder across the BRP from the MST (35.313571, -82.953988).  Hike is around 1.2 miles with 780 feet of EG.  Around 0.85 miles on the MST, just after you start to enter the woods after hiking through an open area, head up around the edge of the clearing on the left.  The trail basically follows the ridgeline and the forest is much more open on this side of the summit.  You still have some briers to contend with between the forest and the summit, but they are not bad in winter.  There are some signs of someone trying to maintain the trail through the briers but that wont last long.
track_title: W4C/WM-008 - Rough Butt Bald via Haywood Gap

track_notes: Following KW4JMs notes, I followed his points to a spot still in the woods at the corner of the Jackson/Haywood county line and wet up there in the AZ. Dean ~ K2JB
This is the track that follows Scott KZ4M notes.  It ends in the AZ but proceeding further up towards the summit is still briar free.
